        <p class="card-text">
        <p>Hospital records are comprehensive documents that capture a wide range of information about patients, their encounters with healthcare providers, the payers responsible for their medical expenses, and the procedures they undergo. These records are crucial for ensuring continuity of care, supporting clinical decision-making, and facilitating billing and reimbursement processes.</p>
        <ul>
            <li class="mb-2">
                <p><b>Patient records</b> typically include personal information such as name, date of birth, and contact details, as well as medical history, allergies, and current medications. This information helps healthcare providers understand the patient's background and tailor their care accordingly. Accurate and up-to-date patient records are essential for preventing medical errors and ensuring that patients receive appropriate and timely care.</p>

            </li>
            <li class="mb-2">
                <p><b>Encounter records</b> document each interaction a patient has with the healthcare system, whether it's a visit to a primary care physician, a hospital admission, or an emergency room visit. These records include details such as the reason for the encounter, the findings from physical examinations, diagnostic test results, and the treatment plan. Encounter records are vital for tracking the patient's progress over time and coordinating care among different healthcare providers.</p>
            </li>
            <li class="mb-2">
                <p><b>Payer records</b> contain information about the entities responsible for covering the cost of the patient's care, such as insurance companies, government programs, or the patients themselves. These records include details about the patient's insurance coverage, policy numbers, and the terms of coverage. Accurate payer records are essential for ensuring that healthcare providers are reimbursed for their services and for minimizing the risk of billing errors and fraud.</p>
